The St. Lucie Transportation Planning Organization (TPO) has requested the service of
Tindale-Oliver & Associates (TOA) to review the current traffic count practices used by
County and Cities to develop recommendations concerning how to select traffic count
locations, frequency of performing traffic counts, quality control techniques to determine
the reasonableness of the traffic count data, and the overall management of historical
traffic count data and its use in various planning and engineering processes and
studies. To develop recommendations, the consultant interviewed members of County
and City departments currently responsible for traffic counts, as well as the departments
This technical memorandum was prepared to summarize the data collection phase of
the study, and is organized into three major sections including this introduction, with
supporting appendices. The remaining sections are summarized below.
documents on site Interviews and Conference Calls with county, city and
FDOT staff, where past and current count practices were discussed, as well as desired
changes and improvements to the traffic count programs.
documents the Data Collected and compiled for use in the study. This
section includes summaries of information collected during the interviews and
conference calls and data provided by TPO, county, city, and FDOT staff.
The Appendices contain data worksheets that supplement the summaries of selected
data items contained in Sections 2 and 3.
With the purpose of identifying traffic count practices, a series of on site interviews and
conference calls were conducted. A list of describing the desired data necessary to
complete the Traffic Count Program evaluations was prepared (Data Needs Memo) and
provided to the TPO’s Project Manager before the project kick-off meeting. The Data
Needs Memo has been included as Appendix A. Additionally, a list of questions
concerning the data received, past and current Traffic Count Practices, and GIS and
Concurrency was prepared for the interviews/conference calls. The list of questions

St. Lucie County TPO Review of Current Traffic Count Practices – Data Needs
This memorandum identifies the list of data needs required to undertake the St. Lucie
County Current Traffic Count Practices and Development of a Standardized Traffic
Count Methodology Project in accordance with the project scope. All data will be
collected through the Transportation Planning Organization’s (TPO) Project Manager. It
is noted that data needs relate all the agencies involved in the management, collection,
review, quality control and reporting of traffic counts and the use of traffic count data by
the various county and city departments, including FDOT. The following summarizes the
1. Organization Charts and Staffing, both permanent and part time
2. Traffic Data Collection Operating Processes and Procedures for the county, cities
3. Data Sharing Agreements including agreements between FDOT and the County
4. Inventory of Equipment used to Perform Counts:
a. Traffic Count Locations and assignment of traffic counts to analysis segments
b. Frequency of collection of traffic counts
d. Formats of Raw Traffic Count Data (15 minute interval or 1 hour interval as
e. Traffic count adjustment factors (peak season, Average Annual Daily Traffic
f. Spreadsheets, Databases, and GIS Data Coverage and related specialized
h. Quality Control practices of traffic count data
j. Count Statistics and Graphics (if produced)
6. Traffic counts performed by consultants on behalf of governmental agencies,
including the name and contact information of the consultant, contract price and
most recent and/or planned traffic counts
a. Level of Service Analysis Spreadsheets
b. Any additional data and analyses, including turning movement data and
refined level of service analysis completed for Kings Highway and Midway
c. Concurrency Management Tracking System and Data
a. Last two fiscal years, current year and next year personnel and operating
b. Last two fiscal years, current year and next year capital budgets
9. Traffic Count Programs Contact Information (names and e-mail addresses) for:
c. City of Port St. Lucie
d. Florida Department of Transportation District 4

have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact me.
